egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Early Dynastic Coffin
egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: The coffins of the Early Dynastic Period were intended for a contracted burial with the body in a fetal position. This coffin was excavated at Kafr Tarkhan near the Faiyum by Sir W.M.F. Petrie.

egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Ishtar
egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: Ishtar is the goddess of love, war, beauty, and sacrifice in wars in Mesopotamia civilizations. The Sumerians called her the Queen of Paradise, and her temple was located in the city of Warka, which is the morning and evening star.

egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Disure Coffin
egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: Red/ Black/ Yellow/ White.very Early 18th Dynasty Coffin. Translation by: DAVID P SILVERMAN, 7 DEC 1988

egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Akhnaton Prayer Relief Fragment
egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: This polychrome fragment of a column depicts Akhnaton offering incense to his sole god, the Aton, and being blessed by the hieroglyph for “life” in return. The cartouches indicate that this column dates to early in Akhnaton's reign, no later than year nine.

egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Coffin Fragment
egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: S Note - Wearing a Long Wig with Hands Crossed Over the Chest.

egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: Not Avaliable

egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: Not Avaliable

egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Pot
egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: Early Assyrian from the ruins of Asshur, the First Assyrian Capital. The pot was built up by hand and not formed on a potter's wheel. Not Far From 2000 BCEE.

egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Contract Tablet Fragment
egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: Not Avaliable

egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: Brown

egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Swimming Cattle Relief
egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: This swimming cattle relief dates from the First Intermediate Period and is made of limestone. This peiod was a time of political collapse in Egypt as a result of the low inundation of the Nile caused by a drought in central Africa.

egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Offering Door of Henuti
egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: Offering doors were the altars of the tombs, a place for the family to deliver funerary offerings to the deceased. This door is dedicated to the Lady Henuti, whose titles are not listed. The image of the lady appears to have been changed in antiquity,
egyptian_museum_artifacts.type of object: Funerary Architecture Funerary Ritual Objects/ Scul Sculpture Old Kingdom

egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Shedy-Ptah Relief Fragment
egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: H-27.1 Translation by: MAX GUILMOT, 21 JUNE 1967/ N.Strudwick, JEA, v.71, 1985

egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Weny Fragment
egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: H-27.5 Translation by: GRANT SCHAR, ASST CURATOR, MARCH 1988

coptic_museum_artifacts.name: Headrest
coptic_museum_artifacts.description: Headrests were known in Egypt since the Old Kingdom. They are normally composed of a flat rectangular base, a central shaft, and a curved neck support. The headrest sometimes contains a spell to preserve and support the head.

coptic_museum_artifacts.name: Faience Tiles
coptic_museum_artifacts.description: These tiles are from the Djoser pyramid complex. They date from the Third Dynasty and are made of faience. They were excavated from the ruins of the step pyramid's subterranean structures. The walls were lined with them in imitation of the matting that covered the walls of the royal residence during the Third Dynasty.

coptic_museum_artifacts.name: Relief Fragment
coptic_museum_artifacts.description: Carved in sunk relief with the figure of a lady facing left and wearing a broad collar and shoulder straps, three lines of inscription above.

coptic_museum_artifacts.name: Husband and Wife
coptic_museum_artifacts.description: Husband and wife are portrayed in an intimate pose on this unusual relief from the First Intermediate Period. The wife is indentified as Senet, the wife whom he loves, emphasizing both the importance of women in this period and personal affection.

museum_islamic_arts_artifacts.name: Kohl Grinding Pallet
museum_islamic_arts_artifacts.description: Pallet for grinding found by the side of Mentuhotep's temple, Thebes, Upper Egypt. White/ Orange/ Brown/ Tan

museum_islamic_arts_artifacts.name: Amenemhet Iii Cylinder Seal
museum_islamic_arts_artifacts.description: L-2.9 Translation by: David O'Connor, U Penn, March 17, 1989

museum_islamic_arts_artifacts.name: Senebi the Overseer
museum_islamic_arts_artifacts.description: The ka was believed to need an alternative home in case of damage to the body. Images such as this one were made as a focus for the ka of the deceased, who is an overseer named Senebi.

manial_palace_museum_artifacts.name: Plowing Man Model
manial_palace_museum_artifacts.description: Cattle were useful not only for meat, but also as draft animals. Farming was the primary occupation of the ancient Egyptian population. These small-scale grave goods were gradually collected over the owner's lifetime. Some show signs of having been played with by the children of the home.

manial_palace_museum_artifacts.name: Battle Axe
manial_palace_museum_artifacts.description: Dark Brown/ Brown/ Light Brown/ White

manial_palace_museum_artifacts.name: Boat Model
manial_palace_museum_artifacts.description: Beige/Grey-White with Blue, Black, Red Oxide, and White Paint

manial_palace_museum_artifacts.name: Meshet Coffin
manial_palace_museum_artifacts.description: L-179.1 Her name means female crocodile. coffin matches that in the Brooklyn collection, Asyut

manial_palace_museum_artifacts.name: Mirror/ Papyrus Shaped Handle
manial_palace_museum_artifacts.description: Green/ Black An unusually well preserved hand mirror. Its handle is shaped like the open papyrus plant. When not in use, it was kept in a leather case to keep it bright.

barque_solaire_museum_artifacts.name: Offering Table
barque_solaire_museum_artifacts.description: Brown/ Beige. Top Center Square Carved in Shallow Relief. Contains a Bell-Shaped Figure Above and a Leg of Beef Below, Flanked By Loaves of Bread and Libation Vases. Bands of Glyphs in Sunk Relief Run Around Border. Four Distinct Bands

barque_solaire_museum_artifacts.name: Shawabti Box with Lid
barque_solaire_museum_artifacts.description: The Shemyat, or Chantress, of Amun-Re, Djed-Ma'at-Ius-Ankh, was the owner of this box made for her collection of shabtis, or worker images, in her tomb.

barque_solaire_museum_artifacts.name: Funerary Boat
barque_solaire_museum_artifacts.description: This funerary boat was made to fulfill a pilgrimage in the Afterlife; the need to visit Abydos, the holy place in Egypt where the god Osiris was believed to have been entombed. This boat includes the coffin of the deceased and even the mourning wife, acting out the role of Isis.

barque_solaire_museum_artifacts.name: Brewery Tomb Model
barque_solaire_museum_artifacts.description: Beer was one of the staples of the ancient Egyptian diet and was a necessity for the Afterlife, as well. Tomb models such as this were as good as having live workers in the Afterlife. This model was included in a tomb to provide perpetual beer for the tomb owners.

barque_solaire_museum_artifacts.name: Boat Model
barque_solaire_museum_artifacts.description: Grey/ Black/ Green/ Blue/ Red/ Yellow/ Brown/ Rust/ White

abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.name: Granary Model
abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.description: Granaries were required in the Afterlife, to assure an endless supply of grain, and models such as this one filled the need. It even includes a scribe to record the amount of grain placed in the granary, to ensure that no theft occurred.

abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.name: Kohl Jar
abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.description: Black/ Green - Mottled Color Small kohl jar used to contain cosmetics to beautify the eyes.

abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.name: Lute-Player Ring
abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.description: Blue-Green Faience Ring. Egyptian cut-away figures in bezel shows 2 anthropoid forms.Girl playing lute, 18th Dynasty

abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.name: Seal Amulet
abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.description: L-3.3 Translation by:Translation by: David O'Connor, U Penn, March 17, 1989.

abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.name: Hatshepsut Cylinder Seal
abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.description: L-2.3 Translation by: David O'Connor, U Penn, March 17, 1989.

abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.name: Pendant Necklace/Double Strand
abdeen_palace_museum_artifacts.description: Ladder-shaped necklace, made of round varigated beads. The rungs are made of shells. With Pendant.

imhotep_museum_artifacts.name: Bead Network
imhotep_museum_artifacts.description: Composed of 3,020 Cylindrical Beads, and 725 Round Beads = 3745

imhotep_museum_artifacts.name: Amenhotep III Kohl Tube
imhotep_museum_artifacts.description: Tube for eye-paint (kohl) with cartouche of Amenhotep III. Brown. Translation by: David P. Silverman

imhotep_museum_artifacts.name: Mirror with Hathor Head Handle
imhotep_museum_artifacts.description: Mirror with blade set in handle of grey steatite carved with heads of the goddess Hathor alternating with the ankh, or looped cross, the sign of eternal life. A reflection was a very powerful thing to people of the ancient world, and mirrors were used in religious and magical rituals.

imhotep_museum_artifacts.name: Senet Board
imhotep_museum_artifacts.description: This senet board dates from the New Kingdom. Senet was the most popular board game for the ancient Egyptians and was played by people from all walks of life. This senet board is made out of cedar and was therefore the property of a moderately wealthy household.

grand_egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Faience Shabti
grand_egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: Shabti of Pa-hws-mst, the Overseer of the Treasury. Faience shabtis became standard and common due to the ease of their mass production, During the Late Period, vast numbers of shabtis were placed in each tomb.

grand_egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Ahnes-Sa-Pa-Iry Stele
grand_egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: H-17.3 Translation by: MOHAMED SALEH, CAIRO MUSEUM, 18 SEPTEMBER 1979

grand_egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Mirror/ Dancing Girl Handle
grand_egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: Brown/ Dark Brown Mirror with handle in form of dancing girl supporting a lotus motif.

grand_egyptian_museum_artifacts.name: Standing Sekhmet
grand_egyptian_museum_artifacts.description: Pharaoh Amenhotep III ordered that up to 730 images of the goddess Sekhmet be created and installed in his mortuary temple to beseech her healing help for his illnesses. The images were later moved to Karnak, and this is presumed to be one of them. In her right hand Sekhmet holds an ankh; in the left, a lotus.

alexandria_national_museum_artifacts.name: Pharaoh's Offering
alexandria_national_museum_artifacts.description: This rare stele is dedicated by the chief of police of the port of Abydos, Hel-Hor, or Hat-Hor, in honor of Osiris and Isis. Translation by: ETIENNE DRIOTON, 10 MAY 1955

alexandria_national_museum_artifacts.name: Disure Coffin
alexandria_national_museum_artifacts.description: Red/ Black/ Yellow/ White.very Early 18th Dynasty Coffin. Translation by: DAVID P SILVERMAN, 7 DEC 1988

alexandria_national_museum_artifacts.name: Pyramidion
alexandria_national_museum_artifacts.description: New Kingdom, may be the scribe Ahmose of the Amarna period, Theban tomb is appropriate location and date, one side is etched out.

library_of_alexandria_museum_artifacts.name: Beer Jar
library_of_alexandria_museum_artifacts.description: This jar was most likely used for the drinking of beer. Its most notable feature is its rounded bottom. This did not allow the consumer to set it down on the floor or table.

library_of_alexandria_museum_artifacts.name: Jar
library_of_alexandria_museum_artifacts.description: Small Squat Jar with Black Concentric Circular Decorations. Late Empire

Akhnaton Prayer Relief Fragment
library_of_alexandria_museum_artifacts.description: This polychrome fragment of a column depicts Akhnaton offering incense to his sole god.

open_museum_at_karnak_artifacts.name: Scribe's Canopic Jar
open_museum_at_karnak_artifacts.description: This canopic jar dates from the Nineteenth Dynasty and is made of calcite pigment and gilt. It belonged to a scribe in the treasury of ancient Egypt.

open_museum_at_karnak_artifacts.name: Shabti of Men
open_museum_at_karnak_artifacts.description: Men was the father of the sculptor Thutmose, perhaps the most famous sculptor in all of Egyptian history.

open_museum_at_karnak_artifacts.description: Tutankhamun, perhaps the most famous pharaoh of ancient Egypt, is the king depicted in this fragment of a sculpture.

luxor_museum_artifacts.name: Apis Bull Head Mummy
luxor_museum_artifacts.description: In the Memphite creation myth the god Ptah was believed to have created the universe and the deities via the thoughts in his heart and by speaking words. He was the patron god of craftsmen and artisans.
luxor_museum_artifacts.material: Animal Remains/ Linen/ Glass/ Argonite/ Obsidian/ Rope

luxor_museum_artifacts.name: Grape Cluster
luxor_museum_artifacts.description: The homes and gardens of Amarna were large and well-planned. This decorative grape cluster was once fitted around the edge of a window to give the impression of a permanent grape arbor.

luxor_museum_artifacts.name: Funerary Cone
luxor_museum_artifacts.description: Clay cone (tan) inscribed with hieroglyphs on the surface. Cones inscribed with the name of the deceased were embedded in the walls of the tombs. Translation by: DAVID P. SILVERMAN, 1988

luxor_museum_artifacts.name: Wedjat Eye
luxor_museum_artifacts.description: Yellow faience glazed wedjat eye. Brown brow line and pupil. Striated nose-marking. Reverse has brown smudge at lash line.

luxor_museum_artifacts.name: Shawabti
luxor_museum_artifacts.description: Brown/ Rust/ Tan/ Light Brown/ Black

mummification_museum_artifacts.name: Faience Ball
mummification_museum_artifacts.description: This faience ball dates from the New Kingdom and is made of faience. The goddess Hathor was believed to be particularly fond of the color blue.

mummification_museum_artifacts.name: Judgment Scene
mummification_museum_artifacts.description: The ibis-headed god Thoth, or Djehuti in ancient Egyptian, was the Scribe of Judgment.

mummification_museum_artifacts.name: Ba
mummification_museum_artifacts.description: Blue/ White/ Green/ Black/ Red Text by: Zahi Hawass

crocodile_museum_artifacts.name: Seated Germa
crocodile_museum_artifacts.description: H-24.9 Translation by: MAX GULIMOT, 21 JUNE 1967

crocodile_museum_artifacts.name: Wesekh Collar
crocodile_museum_artifacts.description: The broad or wesekh collar protected the body of the deceased in the coffin. An actual wesekh collar was placed on the mummy, while a back-up wesekh collar was painted on the wrappings as well.

crocodile_museum_artifacts.name: Mummy (from Usermontu's Coffin)
crocodile_museum_artifacts.description: This male mummy has long been an enigma. He does not display the traditional style of mummification of the time period of the coffin in which he arrived.

crocodile_museum_artifacts.name: Canopic Jar and Lid
crocodile_museum_artifacts.description: Brown/ Light Brown Translation by: MAX GUILMOT , 25 AUGUST 1973 (see artifact file for copy)

crocodile_museum_artifacts.name: Ta'awa Coffin
crocodile_museum_artifacts.description: The Lady of the House Ta'awa was from a very prominent family of the Saite Period. Her father, Hori, was priest of Montu, Lord of Thebes, and relative of Besenmut.

crocodile_museum_artifacts.name: Cylinder
crocodile_museum_artifacts.description: Steel Blue, Tan Brown, Black. Molded in sunk relief with a rrieze of seated deities, including a falcon headed divinity, Hapy, and Ptah, the two fragmentary lines of inscription containing an invocation offering.

nubia_museum_artifacts.name: Shawabti/ Overseer
nubia_museum_artifacts.description: Light Green/ Brown/ Black/ Tan/ Yellow-Green

nubia_museum_artifacts.name: Panel
nubia_museum_artifacts.description: Brown These extremely well-carved hieroglyphs were executed in sunk relief. The signs themselves are cut below the level of the surrounding surface.
